R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document.

Tables

By default, R Markdown displays data frames and matrixes as they would be in the R terminal (in a monospaced font). If you prefer that data be displayed with additional formatting you can use the knitr::kable function.

library(knitr)
kable(mpg[1:5,], caption="Table")
Table
manufacturer model displ year cyl trans drv cty hwy fl class
audi a4 1.8 1999 4 auto(l5) f 18 29 p compact
audi a4 1.8 1999 4 manual(m5) f 21 29 p compact
audi a4 2.0 2008 4 manual(m6) f 20 31 p compact
audi a4 2.0 2008 4 auto(av) f 21 30 p compact
audi a4 2.8 1999 6 auto(l5) f 16 26 p compact

Plots

The ages of 10 first year university students are 19, 20, 20, 19, 20, 21, 20, 18,18, 20, 20. Draw a barplot of the ages.

x<-c(19,20,20,19,20,21,20,18,18,20,20)
barplot(table(x),xlab="Age", ylab="Frequency", col=c("green", "red", "blue",   "black"))

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

Barplot of maths grades

library(readxl)
grades <- read_excel("/Users/admin/Desktop/grades.xlsx")
maths=grades$Maths
Maths.freq=table(maths)
barplot(Maths.freq)

ggplot

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Aesthetic mappings

You can add a third variable, like class, to a two dimensional scatterplot by mapping it to an aesthetic. An aesthetic is a visual property of the objects in your plot. Aesthetics include things like the size, the shape, or the color of your points.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color=class))
